        "text": "Post by spiderwort on\n\nA few for me:\n\nIn John Ford's The Searchers (1956) the desert provides much adversity for Wayne and Hunter as they trek through winter and summer to find their lost girl.\n\nVictor Sjöström's The Wind (1928) creates a beautiful semi-mythical tale out of the desert landscape with a lot of help from Lillian Gish (and the wind).\n\nThe mountainous desert landscape in John Huston's The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (1948) becomes a character in the narrative as the men mine for its gold.\n\nRobert Aldrich's The Flight of the Phoenix (1965) is the perfect illustration of how the desert landscape becomes the antagonist in the story.\n\nNicolas Roeg's Walkabout (1971) beautifully explores the Australian Outback.\n\nPhilip Noyce's Rabbit-Proof Fence (2002) tells the heartbreaking story of three Australian aboriginal girls crossing 1500 miles of the Outback to return to their true home.\n\nPost by teleadm on\n\nDestination Gobi 1953 Robert Wise, Richard Widmark, Don Taylor, Max Showalter. In 1944, US Navy specialists run a weather station in the Gobi desert where they are harassed by Japanese warplanes but aided by local Mongol nomads.\n\nThe Black Tent 1956 Brian Desmond Hurst, Donald Sinden, Anthony Steel, Anna-Maria Sandri. In the African desert, a British soldier romances the native chief's daughter and helps the tribe fight off a Nazi attack.\n\nThe Desert Song 1953 H. Bruce Humberstone, Kathryn Grayson, Gordon MacRae, Steve Cochran. Shiek Yousseff, poses as a friend of the French while secretly plotting to overthrow them. Apposing Yousseff are the Riffs, whose secret leader, The Red Shadow, is Paul Bonnard, a professor who is studying the desert, and whose attacks on the supply trains intended for Yousseff keep the Riff villages in food. Foreign Legion General Birabeau arrives to conduct an investigation, accompanied by his daughter, Margot. Birabeau hires Bonnard to tutor her, and she is attracted to a Legionaire captain, Claud Fontaine. While the general, Bonnard and Fontaine pay a visit to Yousseff, an American newspaper man, Benji Kidd, discovers a secret way in and out of Yousseff's palace, with the aid of Azuri, a dancing girl in love with Bonnard. The latter is forced to resume his role as the Riffs leader, and kidnap Margot until he can convince her of Yousseff's treachery. But Yousseff's men attack the Riff camp and take Margot prisoner. There are earlier versions too.\n\nHidalgo 2004 Joe Johnston, Viggo Mortensen, Omar Sharif, Zuleikha Robinson. In 1890, a down-and-out cowboy and his horse travel to Arabia to compete in a deadly cross desert horse race.\n\nLa battaglia di El Alamein / The Battle of El Alamein 1969 Giorgio Ferroni, Frederick Stafford, George Hilton, Michael Rennie. June 1942 El Alamein: Rommel swept towards the River Nile. The fall of Egypt and the all important Suez Canal seems inevitable. Italian and German scouts race towards Alexandria. Mussolini has given explicit orders that Italy's forces were to reach the city first.\n\nSands of the Kalahari 1965 Cy Endfield, Stanley Baker, Stuart Whitman, Susannah York . After a small aircraft crashes in the Kalahari Desert, one of the seven passengers decides that his survival chances would increase if he would eliminate the other men in the group.\n\nThe Living Desert 1953 James Algar\n\n. Disney Documentary of the live of flora and fauna in a desert in the US. Death Valley and other places.\n\nPost by teleadm on\n\nBeau Geste 1939 William A. Wellman, Gary Cooper, Ray Milland, Robert Preston. Three adopted English brothers join the French Foreign Legion in North Africa, after one of them steals their adoptive family's famous heirloom sapphire. Sahara\n\nMarch or Die 1977 Dick Richards, Gene Hackman, Terence Hill, Catherine Deneuve. During the 1920s, French Foreign Legion Major William Foster's unit is protecting an archaeological dig but the discovery of an Arab sacred burial site prompts the angry Arab tribes to attack Foster's small garrison. Sahara\n\nThe Four Feathers 1939 Zoltan Korda, John Clements, Ralph Richardson, C. Aubrey Smith. Resigning his commission on the eve of his unit's deployment against Egyptian rebels, a British officer seeks to redeem his cowardice by secretly aiding his former comrades - disguised as an Arab. When his unit is overwhelmed and captured by the rebels, the hero finds an opportunity to return the 'feathers' of cowardice sent to him by his former comrades by freeing them. Sudan desert.\n\nAli Baba and the Forty Thieves 1944 Arthur Lubin, Maria Montez, Jon Hall, Turhan Bey. A boy prince, raised by forty thieves, takes revenge on the Mongol invaders who murdered his father and stole his kingdom. Coral Pink Sand Dunes in Utah used in desert scenes.\n\nPost by manfromplanetx on\n\nBeloye solntse pustyni . White Sun of the Desert (1970) ... Highly Recommended\n\nA classic 'Eastern' or Ostern film of the Soviet Union one of the most popular Russian films of all time. Its blend of action/adventure, comedy, music and drama is highly entertaining.\n\nAt the end of the Russian Civil War, Red Army soldier Fyodor Sukhov is ordered to guard the harem of a guerrilla leader and to lead them to safety...\n\nLocation filming was around the western shores of the Caspian Sea and the dunes \"Karakum Desert, Mary, Turkmenistan\", Soviet Union."
